        "contentSnippet": "Analog, Digital, and Computer-Based Instruments Instruments are tools used to measure, record, and analyze physical quantities such as temperature, pressure, or speed. They help technicians, engineers, and students collect accurate data for monitoring or testing. These instruments can be classified into three main types: analog, digital, and computer-based. Each type has its own characteristics, advantages, and uses. Common Types of Instruments and Their Features Analog instruments use continuous signals to represent measurements and display results using pointers, dials, or scales. They are commonly seen in devices such as analog ammeters, voltmeters, pressure gauges, and thermometers. Digital instruments display readings in numeric form on an LCD or LED screen. They use discrete (binary) signals, which make them more accurate and easier to read than analog instruments. Examples include digital multimeters, digital thermometers, and digital tachometers. Computer-based instruments use computers or microprocessors to process, record, and analyze data. These instruments allow data logging, graphing, and automation for precise monitoring. Common examples are oscilloscopes with PC inte"
