        "contentSnippet": "The human body uses food as its main energy source. However, before it can be utilized, food must first undergo a series of digestion processes. During DIGESTION, complex food molecules are broken down into simple food molecules, small enough to enter the bloodstream and be absorbed by the body cells. These processes are carried out by the DIGESTIVE SYSTEM, the organ system responsible for breaking down food into its usable components. The Functions of the digestive system are to: 1. INGESTION. Food and water are taken into the body through the mouth. 2. DIGESTION. The food that is taken into the body is broken down during the process of digestion from complex molecules to smaller molecules that can be absorbed. Digestion consists of mechanical digestion, which involves the chewing of food and the mixing of food with digestive tract secretions, and chemical digestion, which is accomplished by digestive enzymes that are secreted along the digestive tract. 3. ABSORPTION. The small molecules that result from digestion are absorbed through the walls of the intestine for use in the body. Water, electrolytes, and other nutrients, such as vitamins and minerals, are also absorbed. 4. DEFEC"
