        "title": "FIN_Q1_LAS&TN_Math9_Consolidated_1-40.pdf",
        "sourcePage": "https://sites.google.com/deped.gov.ph/deped-lrportal/dlp-materials/dlp-grade-9/quarter-1",
        "downloadUrl": "https://drive.google.com/uc?id=1XxmpayX0dAEYmkkJ2RKAog5nsuwRr3zY&export=download",
        "contentSnippet": "Undefined terms Description Mathematical Model Point • shows an exact location in space. • has no size, width, or depth—just position. • is named points using capital letters. • R (point R) box corner A Line • is a straight path that goes on forever in both directions. • has length and width, but no thickness. • is named using two points on the line or a lowercase letter. A B l line l or 𝐴𝐵⃡ or 𝐵𝐴⃡ string Plane • is a flat surface that goes on forever in all directions. • has length and width, but no thickness. • is named plane by using three non- collinear points or a capital script letter. R E B S plane N or plane RES or plane RBS (any 3 non-collinear points) paper TASK: 1. Imagine you're helping a friend who really wants to learn. In three kind and simple sentences, explain to your classmate who was absent during the discussion what a point, a line, and a plane are. 2. Enumerate three real -life examples that represent a point, a line, and a plane . Choose objects that are familiar or meaningful to you and explain why they remind you of these geometric ideas. You may also include examples that show care for others, nature, or your community. Dynamic Learning Program S.Y. 2025-20"
