        "contentSnippet": "Classifying Triangles Triangles are classified into different types based on their angles and sides. In terms of angles, they fall into three main categories: acute, right, and obtuse triangles. Each type is defined by the measure of its angles, distinguishing them from one another. Acute and obtuse triangles are both considered oblique triangles, meaning they are triangles that do not have a right angle. Sum of Angles in a Triangle - The sum of the interior angles of any triangle is always 180°. This is a key property that is true for all triangles, regardless of their type. Example: Given: Triangle ABC with ∠A = 60° and ∠B = 50°. Find ∠C. To find ∠C, recall that the sum of the three angles is 180° Step 1: Get the sum of the measures of ∠A and ∠B Þ∠A + ∠B = 110°. Step 2: Subtract: 180° - 110° = 70°. Therefore, ∠C = 70°. Since all the angles (60°,50°,70°) are less than 90°, △ABC is an acute triangle. Exercises: Draw the triangle and find the missing angle. Classify whether the triangle is right, obtuse, or acute. 1. In △PQR, ∠P=55° and ∠Q=20°. Find ∠R 2. In △ABC, ∠A=75° and ∠B=60°. Find ∠C 3. In △DEF, ∠D=45°and ∠E=45°. Find ∠F. Reflection Questions: How does knowing angle-side rela"
