        "contentSnippet": "Lesson Information Afro-Latin American music developed during the time of colonization in the Americas. Africans who were brought as slaves carried their rhythms, chants, and percussion instruments, which were lively and connected to dance and community. When they arrived, these African traditions blended with European influences such as the guitar, violin, and brass instruments brought by Spanish and Portuguese colonizers. The music also absorbed indigenous practices, including the use of native flutes and drums. This fusion of cultures gave birth to new musical styles. Samba in Brazil grew from African rhythms with European harmonies. In Cuba, the rumba carried African drumming but later included Spanish melodies. In Argentina, the tango showed European instruments mixed with African rhythm. In Puerto Rico, the salsa became a lively community dance. Afro-Latin American music is more than entertainment—it tells stories, celebrates life, and reflects the struggles, resilience, and identity of the people who created it. Interactive Activity: Chart - Historical Influences on Afro-Latin American Music Historical Influence Example (Music/Dance) Short Description African rhythms & chant"
